	
		<article id="post-33" class="post-33 page type-page status-publish hentry"	<header class="page-header">
		<h1 class="page-title">한국 항공우주 산업</h1>
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->
	<div class="entry-content">
		<hr />
<p class="one-half"><img class="size-full wp-image-138 aligncenter" alt="jet-fighter" src="wp-content/uploads/2014/02/jet-fighter.jpg" width="1200" height="512" /><br />
In 2010 the Korean aerospace industry <b class="green">grossed over USD 2.4 billion owning 0.6% of the global market</b>. The Korean aerospace industry has a strong focus on military aircraft and parts, through many government foreign investment initiatives in military projects.<br />The countries keys successes in the field have been in <b class="green">military related projects from ‘F-X’ projects, initial production of KHP projects and follow-up production of T-50 line aircraft</b>.<br />*However, there has been a notable increase of exports in civilian exports <b class="green">through alliances with Boeing and Airbus</b>.<br />
<br /><small>*Invest in Korea &#8211; aerospace</small></p>
<p class="second-half">Korea’s aircraft parts industry has a significant growing importance, as certain parts of the newest passenger planes are manufactured in Korea.<br />This gives rise to potential growth and expansion in the Korean aerospace market. Especially with government support and initiatives such as <b class="green">the Special Tax Treatment Act which aims to attract foreign investment in Korea</b>. The Boeing Training Services Korea(BTSK) came to fruition through such government schemes and support, where by Boeing invested in a Centre to train and instruct new pilots <b class="green">dispatched to Korea, China, Taiwan and Mongolia</b>.<br />BTSK now plans to extend this program and build a <b class="green">new aviation training Centre to promote advanced technologies and develop more sophisticated aviation expertise</b>. This Centre hopes to due to open in 2014.*<br />
<br />
<small>*Invest in Korea &#8211; aerospace</small></p>
